note: Myles Garrett stayed hot in Week 14, posting four solos, one assist, three tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Garrett failed to record a sack for the first time in even games but should get things back on track in Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Maxx was excellent in Week 14, tallying two solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Crosby is up to nine sacks on the season and is back to his top-five form. Treat him as such for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Bonitto was back at it in Week 14, notching three solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Bonitto is up to 12.5 sacks on the season and has recorded at least one sack in each of his last two games. Tap the elite edge rusher as an easy top-10 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Jeffery Simmons showed up in Week 14, tallying two solos, five assists, 1.5 sacks, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Simmons is up to eight sacks and is now just half a sack from his career high. Simmons has recorded at least one sack in three of his last four games and should be counted as a top-25 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Karlaftis was excellent in Week 14, registering three solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Karlaftis has an impressive 26 pressures on the season, which puts him ahead of elite sack artists like T.J. Watt, Danielle Hunter, and Will Anderson. Now sitting at six sacks, Karlaftis has a sack total more commensurate with the havoc he creates for opposing offensive lines. Fire Karlaftis up as a top-15 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

James Pearce stayed hot in Week 14, tallying two solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Pearce is now riding a five game sack streak, in which he has recorded 5.5 of his six sacks on the season. He is not contributing much outside of the sacks, but is flashing surefire DL1 potential. Tap the rookie edge rusher as a DL2 option while he is cooking, including his week against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Granderson showed up in Week 14, racking up four solos, one assist, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Granderson started the season strong but has worked his way into waiver wire territory since Week 6. Feel free to stash Granderson where needed, but do not chase his Week 14 production despite the plus Week 15 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Jalen Redmond continued his impressive play in Week 14, racking up three solos, three assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Redmond is up to five sacks on the season and is starting to get active in the solo department to boot. The Vikings' defensive tackle makes for an easy DT1 play regardless of opponent or lack of byes. Tap him as a DL3/4 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Zach Sieler showed up in Week 14, racking up three solos, one assist, 2.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Sieler hasn't been much of a fantasy option this season, even for those in DT leagues, so hopefully this is a sign that Sieler is ready to heat up for the playoffs. He does have two sacks in his last four games, so stash him where necessary, but look elsewhere for Week 15 regardless of your league size or settings.

Jordan Davis showed up on Monday night, racking up three solos, three assists, 1.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. Davis remains more of a DT league and 16+ team league option, but has shown enough in back-to-back games to get some flex love. Tap Davis as a DT2/flex2 option for a tasty Week 15 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Ferrell went off in Week 13, exploding with six solos, three assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. The 49ers edge rusher is up to four sacks on the season, with three sacks in his last two games. All of his sacks have come in his last five contests. Tap the former top prospect as a DL3/4 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

AQM was elite on Thursday night, stacking three solos, three sacks, and three tackles for loss. Muhammad is suddenly up to nine sacks, putting him on the list with the premier pass rushers in the league. However, 5.5 of his sacks have come in two contests, so the Lions edge rusher remains a boom-or-bust proposition despite the high sack total. Add to that Al-Quadin played just 46 percent of the snaps in Week 14, and AQM is a DL3/4 at best for a neutral-at-best Week 15 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams. With that said, you should absolutely try to find a way to at least flex him regardless of league size.

Tommy Togiai showed up in Week 14, racking up two solos, eight assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Togiai had just a half sack coming into this contest and is not much of a fantasy option despite the strong showing against Kansas City. Look elsewhere for Week 15.

Derrick Brown showed up in Week 13, making an impact with one solo, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Brown has had two splash weeks and one spike week in his last seven games, and sits at four sacks on the year. Tap the talented interior pass rusher as a DL3/4 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Kingsley Enagbare showed up in Week 14, racking up four solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 56 percent of the snaps. Kingsley has just two sacks on the season and has played more than 50 percent of the snaps all season. 12-team league managers obviously need not apply, but those in deeper leagues should look elsewhere as well. Enagbare should be nowhere near starting lineups for Week 15, regardless of league size.

Vita Vea showed up in Week 14, reeling off three solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Vita is up to a cool 4.5 sacks on the season, with one in each of his last two games. Tap Vea as a flex2 option where needed.

Ponder showed up again in Week 13, tallying two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery on a season high 53 percent of the snaps. Elijah earned an expanded role over the previous two weeks and rewarded the coaching staff with multiple splash plays. Tap Ponder as a DL4/flex option for a heavyweight tilt against the Buffalo Bills in Week 15.

Byron Young (the Philly version) showed up in Week 14, posting two solos, six assists, 1.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Young did not have a sack before Week 14, and is not much of a fantasy option for Week 15 despite the standout production and the plus matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders. Look elsewhere for the first round of the fantasy playoffs.

Gray was at it again in Week 14, stacking seven solos, three assists, and one fumble recovery. Gary is locked in as a top-five option for the fantasy playoffs and should be treated as one for a plus Week 15 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Roquan Smith was excellent in Week 14, tallying four solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. Roquan has been solid over the past few weeks, but has not been producing like a top-five option. Treat Roquan as an LB1 play for Week 15 against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Jack Campbell was at it again in Week 14, racking up six solos, six assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Campbell has been elite all season and is a must-start top-five option for the first week of the fantasy playoffs. Start him everywhere for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Ernest Jones was excellent in Week 14, reeling off five solos and six assists. Jones has been a steady LB1 contributor for fantasy managers and has saved some of his best outings for the stretch run. Tap Ernest as a top-15 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Bobby Wagner was at it again in Week 14, reeling off six solos, 10 assists, and one sack. Wagner has been a steady LB1 option all season, and that will not change in Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the New York Giants.

Devin White was excellent in Week 14, tallying 10 solos and nine assists. White has slowed down from his LB1 start, but remains a strong top-15 option for a plus Week 15 option against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Dodson was excellent in Week 14, tallying two solos, one assist, two tackles for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Dodson remains a steady LB2 contributor and should be treated as one despite the neutral-at-best on-paper matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Bolton was excellent in Week 14, tallying six solos, six assists, and two tackles for loss. Bolton has been back to his LB1 form over the last two weeks and can be counted as a top-15 option for a tasty Week 15 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Sherwood was excellent in Week 14, racking up six solos, nine assists, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. Jamien has been a solid LB2 option for IDP managers this season and can be counted as one for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Eric Wilson was excellent in Week 14, racking up two solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Wilson has been an LB1-level producer since stepping into the starting lineup and should be treated, at the very least, as an elite LB1 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Nakobe Dean was excellent in Week 14, posting three solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Nakobe has been the LB7 in fppg since Week 10 and should be treated as a top-15 option for a tasty Week 15 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Quincy was at it again in Week 14, tallying two solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Williams has provided LB1 level production since the Jets tried to demote him, seemingly using it as motivation to play at the level the team and IDP managers expected of him. Fire Quincy up as a top-15 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Azeez was excellent on Sunday night, notching one solo, four assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Al-Shaair has been a solid LB3 option when active and should be treated as such for a tasty Week 15 matchup against an Arizona Cardinals team gifting the most fantasy points to the position.

Devin Lloyd showed up in Week 14, posting one solo, seven assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Lloyd remains a high ceiling, low floor option, but has proved repeatedly that he has LB1 upside. Tap Lloyd as a top-25 option for a tasty Week 15 matchup against the New York Jets.

Devin Bush showed up in Week 14, posting three solos, six assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Bush has struggled for consistency on the season as a whole, but has been on fire since Week 11, checking in as the LB7 in fppg over the last four weeks. Tap Bush as an upside LB2 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Daiyan Henley was excellent in Week 14, racking up six solos, one assist, and one pass defended. Henley has dropped to the LB3 conversation after his elite start to the season, but continues to remind us of his LB2 upside. Tap Daiyan as a top-36 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Shaq Thompson was solid in Week 14, posting three solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. Fantasy managers had hoped for more from Thompson, who is enjoying an expanded role with Terell Bernard sidelined. Add Shaq where possible with an eye on him making at least one more start for the Bills in Week 15.

Alex Anzalone showed up in Week 14, notching four solos, three assists, and three passes defended. Anzalone has produced at an LB2 level over the last two weeks and should be considered a strong LB3/4 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Drue showed up in Week 14, reeling off four solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. Tranquill has not been much of a fantasy option outside of the byes, but makes for an interesting flex play for Week 15, thanks to facing off against his former team in the Los Angeles Chargers, a team that he posted his highest fantasy total since 2022 against back in Week 1.

Owen Pappoe showed up in Week 14, racking up six solos, four assists, and one pass defended on 50 percent of the snaps. Pappoe has been emerging as an option in the middle due to his coverage ability and finally saw an expanded role in Week 14. His performance should earn him some more snaps for Week 15, putting him on the flex radar for those in deeper formats. Those in the deepest of leagues will want to make him a priority add, as he may start for the rest of the season.

Highsmith was a man on a mission on Sunday, helping the Steelers to a win with seven solos, one sack, and three tackles for loss. The Steelers' edge rusher is one of the hottest pass rushers in the league and is now up to 6.5 sacks in his nine games on the season, with five of them coming in his last four contests alone. Tap Highsmith as a DL2 option for a tasty Week 15 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Jalyx Hunt went off in Week 14, reeling off four solos, four assists, 2.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Hunt is suddenly up to 4.5 sacks, but is not much of a fantasy option for those in 12-team leagues. Those in 16+ team leagues can count Hunt as a flex2 option where needed.
Kam Curl showed up in Week 14, racking up three solos, three assists, and one sack. Curl has had his down weeks, but remains a strong DB1 play for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Jeremy Chinn stayed hot in Week 14, posting seven solos, four assists, and one sack. Chinn has registered back-to-back spike weeks thanks to recording at least seven solos in both games. Consider the safety as part of the DB1 conversation for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Emmanwori went bonkers in Week 14, stacking five solos, one assist, one sack, two tackles for loss, one interception, one pass defended, and one blocked kick. The rookie has started to hit his stride since the Seahawks' Week 8 bye, checking in as the DB7 in fppg during that five game span. Fire Emmanwori up as a top-25 option for a tasty Week 15 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

CJGJ showed up in Week 14, notching six solos, four assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Gardner-Johnson has stepped back into fantasy relevance after three straight IDP duds. Still, with three splash weeks since joining the Bears, CJGJ checks in as the DB8 in fppg in that doc game stretch. Tap the Bears' safety as a top-25 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Geno Stone was excellent in Week 14, racking up seven solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Stone has been a DB3 for most of the season, but can be considered part of the top-25 conversation thanks to posting two monster outings in his last three contests. Treat him as such for a plus Week 15 matchup against his former team in the Baltimore Ravens.

Jordan Battle continued to impress in Week 14, tallying five solos, four assists, and one pass defended. Battle has been a top-25 option since Week 7 and can be counted as an elite DB3 play for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Buffalo Bills. Start the Bengals safety where needed.

Reed showed up in Week 14, tallying six solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. Reed has caught fire at the right time for IDP managers and can be counted as a top-25 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Jalen Pitre was excellent in Week 14, tallying four solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Pitre is a solid DB3 option for Week 15, but comes with the type of floor typical of DB3 plays. Start Pitre where needed for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Devon Witherspoon was excellent in Week 14, posting five solos, two assists, one fumble recovery, one interception, and two passes defended. Devon has flashed DB3 value at times, but remains someone to leave on benches outside of CB leagues for Week 15 despite the strong production. Look elsewhere for the first round of the fantasy playoffs.

Jordan Poyer was excellent in Week 14, reeling off six solos and two assists. Poyer is a DB3/4 option at best for the fantasy playoffs, but does have a couple of plus matchups for fantasy managers to exploit if needed. Tap Poyer as such for a plus Week 15 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Kevin Winston was at it again in Week 14, reeling off four solos, one assist, two tackles for loss, and two passes defended. The rookie safety has been on a heater for IDP managers, posting three straight DB1-level outings. There's no reason not to consider Winston a top-25 option as long as he is cooking. The DB4 in fppg over the last three weeks, treat him as such for a plus Week 15 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Harrison Smith was excellent in Week 14, racking up three solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. Smith has slipped to the DB3/4 realm but is still worth a look for Week 15, thanks to what should be a busy night against the Dallas Cowboys on Sunday Night Football.

Kamari Lassiter was excellent in Week 14, racking up five solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended against Kansas City in what was essentially a must win game. The DB6 in fppg since Week 7, Lassiter should be counted as an upside DB2 option, albeit with a low floor. Fire Kam up as a top-25 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Malik was excellent in Week 13, reeling off five solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Mustapha has recorded five or more solos and a tackle for loss in two straight, making him a borderline DB2 option for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Antonio Johnson was solid against Indianapolis, tallying six solos and two assists. Johnson has produced like a strong DB2 option over his last five games and is someone to plug into lineups as a DB3 option where needed. Start him with confidence as a top-36 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the New York Jets.

Adebo showed up in Week 13, serving up eight solos, two assists, and one pass defended. Adebo was on fire prior to the knee injury that knocked him out for five games and can safely once again be viewed as a top-15 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against Washington.

Dane Belton was excellent in Week 13, racking up five solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Belton has been producing at a DB2 level since Week 7 and should be treated as one for a plus Week 15 matchup against Washington.

Hughes stayed hot in Week 14, racking up six solos, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Thanks to chipping in six solos in three straight, Hughes has strung together three consecutive plus outings, forcing his way into the DB3 conversation in the process. Count him as a CB1/DB3 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers on Thursday Night Football.

Rasul Douglas showed up again in Week 14, racking up two assists, one interception, and five passes defended. Rasul has posted multiple spike weeks this season, including in each of his last two games. Douglas is more DB4 than DB3 for Week 15, but can be slotted in as a flex option where needed for Week 15 against Pittsburgh.

Nick Scott showed up in Week 13, notching five solos, four assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Scott is a bye week filler type who is now out of byes to fill. Keep him as emergency depth where roster space allows, but keep him far from your Week 15 lineups, despite the plus matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Avonte Maddox showed up in Week 14, notching six solos, two assists, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Avonte is not a fantasy option despite the strong production. Look elsewhere for Week 15.

Christian Izien showed up in Week 14, notching five solos, three assists, and on
e tackle for loss. Treat Izien as a flex option for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Oliver showed up in Week 14, racking up five solos, four assists, and two passes defended. Oliver has registered five solos in back-to-back weeks; putting him on the DB3 radar. Tap him as a DB3/4 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the  Jacksonville Jaguars.

Benford showed up again in Week 14, tallying one solo, one sack, one tackle for loss, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. Benford has scored a defensive touchdown in back-to-back weeks, but is not someone whose production fantasy managers should be chasing, especially in the fantasy playoffs. Ignore Benford completely, despite the standout production, unless you play in a league with multiple CB spots.

Tony Jefferson showed up in Week 14, reeling off five solos, one interception, and one pass defended. Old man Jefferson has recorded a pick in back-to-back weeks and is worth a look as a flex option in deeper formats. Start Jefferson where needed.

Kool-Aid showed up in Week 14, tallying six solos, one assist, and one pass defended. McKinstry has posted back-to-back spike weeks and makes for a solid flex option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

D.J. Reed showed up in Week 14, reeling off eight solos, one interception, and two passes defended. Reed has sprinkled in a couple of plus outings, but is more of a CB league option than someone those in the playoffs will want to plug into lineups. Look elsewhere for Week 15.
